%S A396562 1,5,2,11,6,3,1,7,16,4,10,5,21,9,12,6,22,10,2,7,20,11,1,31,12,28,9,28,
%T A396562 13,36,10,3,14,11,12,15,5,35,14,16,46,13,25,4,40,14,51,18,13,15,19,1,
%U A396562 15,2,46,20,5,17,61,21,18,41,22,26,19,16,49,23,6,6,24,45
%N A396562 a(n) is the minimal number of integer cubes needed to tile an integer cuboid of volume A033942(n).
%C A396562 For volumes k not in A033942, any 3-factorization had at least one factor 1 and a(k) would be k.
%C A396562 First counterexample to guillotine optimality: a(43) = 25 for V = A033942(43) = 105 = 3*5*7. The best guillotine partition uses 25 cubes, while the true optimum is 32 and requires a nonguillotine arrangement.
%H A396562 Felix Huber, <a href="/A396562/a396562.txt">Maple program</a>
%F A396562 1 <= a(n) <= A033942(n) - A020639(A033942(n))^3 + 1.
%F A396562 a(n) = t for A033942(n) = t*m^3 and positive integers m and t.
%F A396562 a(n) = m^2 + 1 for A033942(n) = m^3 + m^2 and positive integer m.
%F A396562 a(n) = u*v for A033942(n) = t^3*u*v and positive integers t, u, v and u*v cubefree (A004709).
%e A396562 a(43) = 25 for V = A033942(43) = 105 = 3*5*7. The optimal tiling uses two cubes of side 3, four cubes of side 2, and 19 unit cubes, for a total of 25 cubes:
%e A396562   |   layer 1   |   layer 2   |   layer 3   |   layer 4   |   layer 5   |   layer 6   |   layer 7   |
%e A396562   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%e A396562   |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |
%e A396562   |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |
%e A396562   |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    1 1 1    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |
%e A396562   |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |
%e A396562   |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    2 2 1    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |    3 3 3    |
